## Review Notes

* Pascal's Triangle coefficients can also be calculated using the combination formula: [\binom{n}{k} = \frac{n!}{k!(n-k)!}]
* The sum of coefficients in [(a + b)^n] is [2^n] (by substituting [a = 1, b = 1]).
* For [(x + y)^n], the signs in the expansion of [(x - y)^n] alternate: positive, negative, positive...
* The [r]th term (1-indexed) of [(a + b)^n] is: [\binom{n}{r-1} a^{n-(r-1)} b^{r-1}]
* In probability, if an event has probability [p] of success and [q = 1-p] of failure, the probability of exactly [k] successes in [n] trials is: [\binom{n}{k} p^k q^{n-k}]
* When expanding [(a + b)^n], the sum of exponents in each term equals [n].
